<H1>Request for Comments (RFC) Frequently Asked Questions</H1></CENTER>
<HR>

<H3>1) I cannot retrieve the text of an RFC. Why not?</H3>
<BLOCKQUOTE>Some RFC numbers were issued to documents that were never =
actually=20
  published. This explains the occasional gap between numbers.=20
  <P>A few RFCs have been physically lost. If you have a physical =
version of RFC=20
  79, 94, 178, 282, 351, 387, 455, 456, 457, 468, 478, 487, 488, 489, =
491, 496,=20
  500, 501, 504, 506, 508, 513 and 590, please send us a copy. Thanks=20
  <P>Finally, many early RFCs exist only on paper. The RFC Editor has an =
"RFC=20
  Online" project to make the entire RFC series available online. We are =

  currrently working on RFC numbers in the range 1-600. However, this =
process=20
  has necessarily had lowest priority; keeping up with new RFCs must =
take=20
  precedence. It is our objective to make substantial progress towards =
getting=20
  all RFCs online before the end of the year 2000. We are grateful for =
the help=20
  of volunteers in the Internet community, who are entering and nroffing =
text of=20
  the missing RFCs. </P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<H3>2) How do I get an RFC published?</H3>
<BLOCKQUOTE>See <A href=3D"http://www.rfc-editor.org/howtopub.html">How =
To=20
  Publish</A>. </BLOCKQUOTE>
<H3>3) How can I correct an error in a published RFC?</H3>
<BLOCKQUOTE>You cannot. Once an RFC is published, it cannot be changed. =
The=20
  RFCs form an archival series. If the bug is serious, a revised RFC can =
be=20
  written that obsoletes the one in error. </BLOCKQUOTE>
<H3>4) Once my document has been sent to the IESG for review, or =
approved by the=20
IESG for publication, how do I know the RFC Editor has it in their =
queue?</H3>
<BLOCKQUOTE>Please look at the <A=20
  href=3D"http://www.rfc-editor.org/queue.html">RFC Editor Queue</A> =
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<H3>5) How long does it take for a document to become an RFC?</H3>
<BLOCKQUOTE>The time varies greatly from one RFC to another. Publication =
may=20
  be held up for a variety of reasons, including IESG approval, =
inconsistencies=20
  or omissions that show up in editing, or normative references to other =

  documents that must be published earlier or simultaneously. Authors =
should=20
  also be aware that the RFC Queue gets very backed up right before =
meetings of=20
  the IETF. </BLOCKQUOTE>
<H3>6) What can I do to expedite the RFC process?</H3>
<BLOCKQUOTE>READ ALL THE INSTRUCTIONS CAREFULLY. Make sure your document =
is=20
  formatted properly, and the best way to speed up the processing of =
your=20
  document is to create an nroff source file. We have provided a quick =
tutorial=20
  on <A href=3D"http://www.rfc-editor.org/nroff.html">basic =
nroffing</A>.=20
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<H3>7) I just realized my document has typos, or my address or =
affiliation has=20
changed...what do I do?</H3>
<BLOCKQUOTE>You have two options: WAIT until the document has been =
approved=20
  for publication and then send the changes to the <A=20
  href=3D"mailto:rfc-ed@rfc-editor.org">RFC Editor</A>, or wait until =
the 48 hour=20
  approval period to send the RFC Editor the changes. DO NOT send the =
RFC Editor=20
  changes for a document that does not appear in the <A=20
  href=3D"http://www.rfc-editor.org/queue.html">RFC Editor Queue</A>. =
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<H3>8) Will I have a chance to look over my document before it becomes =
an=20
RFC?</H3>
<BLOCKQUOTE>Yes. See <A =
href=3D"http://www.rfc-editor.org/howtopub.html">How To=20
  Publish</A>. </BLOCKQUOTE><!-- Once an RFC is ready to be published, =
author(s) are given=0A=
48 hours to look over their document for editorial nits.  They are=0A=
notified at the beginning of this period via email.  We STRONGLY=0A=
suggest that authors check for spelling errors and missing words and=0A=
that they make sure the references and contact information are up to=0A=
date.  Also, if your document is a MIB we encourage you to take one=0A=
last look at your CODE.  We DO NOT make changes to RFCs once they have=0A=
been published, so please look over your document carefully.=0A=
-->
